  "prompt": "How does the Zika Virus affect men and non pregnant women?",
  "response": "The Zika virus is primarily transmitted through the bite of an infected Aedes mosquito, but it can also be spread through sexual contact, blood transfusions, and from a pregnant woman to her fetus. While much of the concern surrounding Zika has focused on its effects on pregnant women and their babies, it can also affect men and non-pregnant women. Here\u2019s how:\n\n1. **General Symptoms**: In most men and non-pregnant women, Zika virus infection is either asymptomatic or causes mild symptoms. When symptoms do occur, they typically include:\n   - Fever\n   - Rash\n   - Joint pain\n   - Conjunctivitis (red eyes)\n   - Muscle pain\n   - Headache\n\n   These symptoms usually last for several days to a week and rarely require hospitalization. \n\n2. **Guillain-Barr\u00e9 Syndrome (GBS)**: In rare cases, Zika virus infection has been associated with Guillain-Barr\u00e9 Syndrome, a condition in which the immune system attacks the nerves, leading to muscle weakness and, in severe cases, paralysis. This can affect both men and women.\n\n3. **Impact on Reproductive Health**: There is some evidence that Zika virus can affect male reproductive health. The virus has been found in semen, and there are concerns about its potential to impact sperm quality and fertility, though more research is needed in this area.\n\n4. **Sexual Transmission**: Men can transmit the virus to sexual partners, including non-pregnant women, through unprotected sex. The virus can remain in semen longer than in other body fluids, so precautions such as condom use are recommended to prevent transmission, especially if there is a risk of pregnancy.\n\n5. **Long-term Effects**: For most men and non-pregnant women, the long-term effects of the Zika virus are not well understood, but the majority of people recover fully without any lasting health issues.\n\nIt\u2019s important for individuals who may have been exposed to Zika, especially those who are planning to conceive or are in a relationship where pregnancy is a possibility, to consult healthcare providers for guidance on testing and prevention strategies.",
